President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation recognizing December 3rd as the International Day of Persons with Disabilities. In the proclamation, Obama reaffirms the commitment of the United States to ensuring full equality and participation for people with disabilities in all aspects of society. He highlights the contributions made by individuals with disabilities and emphasizes that disability rights are universal rights that should be promoted worldwide. The proclamation also highlights the efforts made by the U.S. government to advance disability rights both domestically and internationally, including the signing of the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities. The proclamation calls on all Americans to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies and activities.